08162nam a22010575i 9780300150322DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20072007ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001503227 a10.12987/97803001503222doi  a(DE-B1597)486633  a(OCoLC)922006879  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPN6071.F47bT54 2007eb 7aSPO0140002bisacsh04a808.803572221 aGilmore, David D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTight Lines :bTen Years of the Yale Anglers' Journal /cDavid D. Gilmore. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the first copy of the Yale Anglers’ Journal appeared in 1996, readers with an interest in fish and fishing have opened the pages of each issue with anticipation and delight. YAJ’s founders suspected that others would share their passion for literature and art related to angling; what they had not fully anticipated was the intensity of enthusiasm from readers and writers everywhere. Perhaps they shouldn’t have been surprised. Statistics tell us that 35 million Americans regularly fish, and among their numbers are presidents and students, old and young, the famous and the unknown, the busy and the idle.This anthology presents a selection of 50 stories, recollections, essays, and poems featured in the Yale Anglers’ Journal during its first remarkable decade. Accompanied by original artwork from James Prosek, these writings all celebrate fish and the experience of fishing, yet they could hardly be more diverse. Some evoke a nostalgic earlier time, others vibrate with excitement, and still others offer a humorous view of life’s surprises. The contributions come from well-known current writers, little-known newcomers, and even authors of antiquity, such as Homer, who had a thing to say about fishing. Anyone who has felt a line pull tight, or is curious to know why the experience has inspired anglers throughout human history, will want to open the pages of this inviting book. “So here is where I came out as I entered my fiftieth year….I believe in a balanced life. I do not want to fish all the time….But I have learned that I am also a person who has to be able to go fishing whenever I can and for as long as I want to go.”-from “Amare O Pescare,” by Howell Raines  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFishingvLiterary collections. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Fishing.2bisacsh1 aAlter, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarca, Dane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Thomas Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehnke, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleakney, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloch, R. Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorden, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowen, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckley, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanegato, Juaquín Hernàndez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Jimmy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaruk, Abu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFong, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFryer, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuria, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb